info.title: Commbox API
info.description:
# Overview The commbox Platform offers several options for integrations with external systems. This document aims to provide all of the information needed for developers to use commbox's resources, be it server based or client-side. ## Getting Started In order to access our APIs, you will need a Brand Access Token. This key is generated when your installation is complete and should be kept secret for all interaction with our resources. ## Main Data Entities and Relationships # REST API ## Overview The commbox REST API allows you to integrate and perform queries to commbox systems.
The API is based on REST principles. It supports GET, POST, and DELETE requests.
Use a GET request to retrieve information from a resource and a POST to update an entity. DELETE removes an entity. After receiving your request, the API sends back an HTTP code as a response in JSON ## Base URI All URLs referenced in the documentation have the following base:
https://api.commbox.io ## Security Considerations The commbox REST API is served over HTTPS. To ensure data privacy, unencrypted HTTP is not supported.
In addition, all requests are required to pass an Access Token for authentication.
The access token is predetermined and provided by commbox. All requests are logged and validated. All parameters must be URL-encoded. ## Structure and Examples ### Request The request must include the module and operation in the URI.
For example, to access an operation called SystemStatus in the Core module, make an HTTP request to –
/Core/SystemStatus

In order to receive specific information regarding a resource, use the provided parameters in the URI.
For example, to access a specific user data in the Core module, make an HTTP GET request to –
/Users/{USER_ID}/Details

In order to change a resource, use an HTTP POST request to the resource URI.
For example, to change a specific user name in the Core module, make an HTTP POST request to –
POST /Users/{USER_ID}/Details
And include the post parameter
data={\"FirstName\":\"FIRSTNAME\", \"LastName\":\"LASTNAME\"

In order to delete a resource, use an HTTP DELETE request to the resource URI.
For example, to change a specific user name in the Core module, make an HTTP DELETE request to –
DELETE /Users/{USER_ID}/

Access Token - As mentioned, all requests have to pass an Access Token to validate authenticity. This can be done by including the token in the URI as a parameter. This token indicates to the system what modules, operations and resources the user has access to.

For example, to access the above update operation, make an HTTP POST request to
POST /Users/{USER_ID}/Details&access_token=<TOKEN>
data={\"FirstName\":\"FIRSTNAME\", \"LastName\":\"LASTNAME\"}

Output Mode - The output mode is JSON
### Response Property | Description ------------- | ------------- status | The HTTP status code for the response description | A more informative message response_time | UTC Timestamp for the operation data | (Optional) Additional output data, varies by operation
### Possible Response Status Codes Status Code | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - 200 | OK | The request was successful 400 | Bad Request | The request could not be understood by the server. Incoming parameters might not be valid 401 | Unauthorized | The supplied credentials, if any, are not sufficient to access the resource 404 | Not Found | The requested resource is not found 429 | Too Many Requests | Too many requests have been made in a short period of time (Throttling) 500 | Server Error | The server could not return the representation due to an internal server error 501 | Not Implemented | The requested operation is not supported (e.g. supports GET but not POST etc.) ### API Calls Examples Our various API can be found under the "API Calls Section" # Webhooks ## Overview The commbox Real-time updates API allow you to integrate to commbox systems and receive on-going updates.
The API updates are push notifications that will be transferred to client endpoints on key triggers (or “Events”) in the commbox logic workflow.
When a change occurs, an HTTP 'POST' request will be sent to the predetermined callback URL provided by the client.
This makes updates more efficient, as they know exactly when a change has happened, and don't need to rely on continuous or even periodic requests when changes aren't happening.
The updates can be transferred as XML objects and should be processed by the receiving client according to this reference document. ## Security Considerations To ensure data privacy, we strongly recommend using an HTTPS callback URL with a strong encrypted certificate. ## Structure and Examples All updates contain a wrapper called “Event” which indicates the subscription source and name of the trigger event. Inside the wrapper will be the actual data relevant to this update. ### Xml Example For a new object that was received on commbox’s servers, an “OnNew” event will be triggered and posted to the client callback URL: # Subscriptions ## Object ### OnNew This event is triggered by the creation of a new object

Example: ### OnNewChild This event is triggered by the creation of a new child object

Example: ### OnNewActivity This event is triggered by the creation of a new activity

Example: ## User This section contains several events that dictate that a change occurred in some commbox monitored user. The change may be a new user or an update of an existing one.
All updates use the same basic structure and must contain a surrounding “Event” property and a “User” property. Additional properties are included as per the exported event. ### OnNew This event is triggered by the creation of a new user

Example: {} ### OnUpdate This event is triggered by an update of a user

Example: {} ### OnUpdateTag This event is triggered by an update of a tag relating to the user

Example: ## Satisfaction This section contains events that describe a customer satisfaction report.
All updates use the same basic structure and must contain a surrounding “Event” property and a “Satisfaction” property. Additional properties are included as per the exported event. ### OnSubmit This event is triggered by a submission of a satisfaction report relating to some object.

Example: 100 excellent ## Form This section contains several events that occurred when a form is created or changed.
All updates use the same basic structure and must contain a surrounding “Event” property and a “Form” property. Additional properties are included as per the exported event. ### OnSubmit This event is triggered when a customer submit a form and the form PDF file is saved on the disk.

Example:
901733 https://apps.commboxdev.io/form... {“field_0”:”Jhon”,”my_own_param”:”1234”}
## Chat This section contains an event that occurred when the user closes the chat window or disconnect. ### OnUserExit This event is triggered when the user closes the chat window or disconnect.

Example: # Single Sign-on and Authentication modules commbox offers several options for authentication and silent login into our systems, in addition to our standard user/password login process. ## Directory Services We allow login for our management site using Directory Services providers (such as Active Directory). To set it up, the Single Sign-On module must be active and the domain, username and password (optional) must be set in the Module Settings tab. Furthermore, every user who wish to login using Directory Services must also set the Username field in the Users Management page. Once configured, the system will try to validate the username and password fields inputted on the login page against the DS server. If successful, the user will be automatically signed in to the system. Else, the system will try to validate the user/password field against the normal Commbox credentials. ## Ticket Authentication We allow login for our management site and some apps using a custom, signed ticket for authentication. The ticket must be signed by the sending party using our API. The signed ticket is then passed and verified by the system. If successful and the provided user identifiers are valid, a session cookie will be created and returned to the user. ### Creating a Ticket The ticket is created using our API "Creating a Ticket" If the ticket is used to login our management site it must include the following parameters: brand name and username (a user with this params must be set up in advance via the managment site) If the ticket is used to login our different apps it must include all the requierd parameters that include on the specific app. For example: firstName, lastName, Phone, email address etc. Once created, tickets are only valid for 60 seconds for the management system and 5 minutes for other applications. ### Sending the Ticket After the ticket has been created and signed, it should be passed by either query string or as a POST parameter. For example: https://manage.commbox.io?brand=BRAND_NAME&ta=TICKET Once the ticket has been verified, the system will validate the additional user parameters that were sent and perform a silent login. Depending on which site was accessed, the relevant parameter will be checked and determine which user should perform the login. Once the entire process is complete and successful, the system will produce a security token in the form of an HTTP cookie that validates further access to the required site. If an existing cookie was found, it will be overwritten and extended. # Integration and Customization Commbox supports a wide variety of client-side integrations and customizations that easily enable seamlessly embedding Commbox into other systems. ## Widgets We enable our sites to be embedded on other web-based platforms. All of our applications are written with responsive web design in mind so that it is possible to embed on all screen sizes. Furthermore, we also provide several premade widgets for embedding our Inbox, Object, and Dashboard. These allow for specific functions and views. ### Inbox Widget This widget displays the main view of our management work area. All interaction is enabled in this view and viewing it requires the user to be logged in. https://manange.commbox.io ### Object Widget This widget displays a specific object (conversation) in our management work area. All object interaction is enabled in this view, just like in the main inbox.

Viewing it requires the user to be logged in and have permission to view the object https://manange.commbox.io/widget/object/XXXXXX ## Manage Client-Side Customization Module We enable our sites to be embedded on other web-based platforms. All of our applications are written with responsive web design in mind so that it is possible to embed on all screen sizes. Furthermore, we also provide several premade widgets for embedding our Inbox, Object, and Dashboard. These allow for specific functions and views. In order to make our product more approachable and suited for many needs, we enable several types of client-side customization. For the Agent Desktop Management application, we allow CSS customization for most page elements as well as specific JavaScript code that executes on some client-side events. These event includes conversation status change and opening customer card but can expanded further. # Data structures This section describes all of the data structures the API recognizes and sends ## Object Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Id | int64 | Object ID. This is a Commbox generated number | StreamId | int64 | Stream ID to which the object is connected | SubStreamId | int64 | Sub Stream ID to which the object is connected | Type | short | The type of the object | Object Types StatusId | string | Current status ID| Object Statuses CreatedTime| datetime | When the object was created | In UTC time FirstResponseTime | datetime | When the first response to the object was registered | In UTC time UpdatedTime | datetime | When the object was last updated | In UTC time PriorityTime | datetime | When the object is currently prioritized | In UTC time NumChilds | int | Number of child objects relating to this parent object | IsManager | bool | Indicates whether this object was created by a manager | NumTags | int | Number of tags assigned to this object| Message| string | The text containing the object’s primary message | Content | JSON string | String containing extended properties of the object | User | object | The user that created the object| User ## Object Child Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Id | int64 | Child ID. This is a Commbox generated number | Type | short | The type of the child | Object Types IsManager | bool | Indicates whether this child was created by a manager | CreatedTime| datetime | When the child was created | In UTC time Message| string | The text containing the child’s primary message | Content | JSON string | String containing extended properties of the child | User | object | The user that created the child| User ## Object Activity log Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Text | string | Text content in the activity log | Source | string | The source of the activity log (optional) | ManagerId | Int64 | The manager who initialize the activity log (optional) | ## Tag Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Id | int64 | Tag ID. This is a Commbox generated number | ## User Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Id | int64 | User ID. This is a Commbox generated number | UniqueId | string(50) | User’s unique identifier. This can be an email, social security number or any other type of unique string determined by the brand administrators | Phone1 | Numeric string(20) | User’s phone number | Always contains country code and without leading + or 00 Phone2| Numeric string(20) | User’s additional phone number | Always contains country code and without leading + or 00 Email | string (255) | User’s email address | FirstName | string (100) | User’s first name | LastName | string (100) | User’s last name | Gender | string (1) | User’s gender | ‘M’ for male, ‘F’ for female Locale | object | User’s locale | Birthday | date | User’s birthday | Date only NumIdentities | int | Number of active identities that are connected to this user | IsManager | bool | Indicates whether this user is a manager | Remarks | string | Free text containing general remarks about the user | Identity | object | Identity object that is connected to the user | User Identity ## User Identity Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Id | int64 | Identity ID. This is a Commbox generated number and used throughout all the updates | Stream Provider Id | string(255) | Identity’s unique identifier as it appears at the original provider | Stream Provider Type | int64 | Type of the original provider | Stream Provider Types Stream Provider Email| string(255) | Identity’s email as it appears at the original provider | UserName | string (100) | Identity’s user name as it appears at the original provider | FirstName | string (100) | Identity’s first name as it appears at the original provider | LastName | string (100) | Identity’s last name as it appears at the original provider | ThumbnailUrl | string (255) | Link to the identity’s profile image | NumObjects | int | Number of objects connected to this identity | ## Manager Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - Id | int64 | Manager ID. This is a Commbox generated number and used throughout all the updates | AsyncAssignedNoResponse | int | Current number of assigned asynchronous objects awaiting response | AsyncAssignedInProccess | int | Current number of assigned asynchronous objects that are being addressed by the manager | SyncAssignedNoResponse| int | Current number of assigned synchronous objects awaiting response (Chat/messenger conversations) | SyncAssignedInProccess | int | Current number of assigned synchronous objects that are being addressed by the manager (Chat/messenger conversations) | FaceToFaceStatus | bool | Returns true if the manager is busy with a face to face object (Voice/Video call) | TotalAsyncAssigned | int | Total number of currently assigned objects | TotalSyncAssigned | int | Total number of currently assigned synchronous objects (Chat/messenger conversations) | ## Object custom indicator Property | Value | Description | Notes ------------- | ------------- | - | - IndicatorId | string | Indicator id (unique name) – to allow updating/ deleting existing indicator | DisplayClass | string | Indicator class. Mandatory only if Icon has not provided | You must provide DisplayClass or an Icon, or both Icon | string | An icon for the indicator. Supports URL. Mandatory only if Icon has not provided (not relevant for DELETE operation) | Title| string | A title for the indicator (not relevant for DELETE operation) | # Enums ## Object Types Text = 0

post.description:
### Parameters Form ID – Form number (as seen in the forms list screen).
Data – A Json string consists of the following fields:
  • streamProviderId – Customer phone number or email (which will be receiving the form)
  • streamProviderType – Identifies which type of value (phone or email) the streamProviderId contains, 4 is email, 5 is phone number.
  • referringObjectId (optional) – When the form link is opened a new form object is created in the system, this object can be linked to another object, for example a chat conversation, so once the form is filled by the customer you will see (in the manage system) the chat conversation with an indicator of the filled form.
  • properties (optional) – a Json string contains initial values for the form fields, so when the customer will open the form its fields will contain those values.
The format is as follows: {“FIELD 1 NAME”: “FIIELD 1 VALUE”, “FIELD 2 NAME”: “FIELD 2 VALUE”, etc…}
Note: You can store your own parameters (which will not affect the form), so when the form is signed you will receive them in the OnSubmit event.

FaceToFaceStatus.description: Returns true if the manager is busy with a face to face object (Voice/Video call)

TotalAsyncAssigned.description: Total number of currently assigned objects

TotalSyncAssigned.description: Total number of currently assigned synchronous objects (Chat/messenger conversations)

IndicatorId.description: Indicator id (unique name) – to allow updating/ deleting existing indicator

DisplayClass.description: Indicator class. Mandatory only if Icon has not provided

Icon.description: An icon for the indicator. Supports URL. Mandatory only if Icon has not provided (not relevant for DELETE operation)

Title.description: A title for the indicator (not relevant for DELETE operation)

Link.description: Optional link for the indicator (not relevant for DELETE operation)
